<!-- ── WATT'S LAW ── -->
<h2 id="power">Power and Ohm's Law — Watt's Law</h2>

<p>
  Combine Ohm's Law with the definition of power (P = V × I) and you get three equivalent power formulas — together called <strong>Watt's Law</strong>:
</p>

<div class="my-8 grid grid-cols-3 gap-3">
  {[
    { formula: 'P = V × I', derived: 'Basic definition', color: 'bg-[#0D1B2A] text-white border-[#E0252E]' },
    { formula: 'P = I² × R', derived: 'Substitute V = IR', color: 'bg-[#1B3A5B] text-white border-blue-400' },
    { formula: 'P = V² ÷ R', derived: 'Substitute I = V/R', color: 'bg-[#0D2547] text-white border-emerald-400' },
  ].map(f => (
    <div class={`rounded-xl border-l-4 p-4 text-center ${f.color}`}>
      <p class="font-mono font-bold text-base mb-1">{f.formula}</p>
      <p class="text-[10px] opacity-70">{f.derived}</p>
    </div>
  ))}
</div>

<!-- ── EXAMPLES ── -->
<h2 id="examples">Practical Examples</h2>

<div class="my-8 space-y-5">
  <!-- Example 1 -->
  <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 overflow-hidden">
    <div class="bg-gray-50 border-b border-gray-200 px-5 py-3 flex items-center gap-2">
      <span class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-[#E0252E] text-white text-xs font-bold flex items-center justify-center shrink-0">1</span>
      <p class="font-bold text-[#0D1B2A] text-sm">Checking a heater element</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-5">
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">A 230 V heater rated at 2 kW. What current does it draw, and what should its resistance measure?</p>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3">
        <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-3 font-mono text-sm text-blue-800">
          I = P ÷ V<br/>
          I = 2000 ÷ 230<br/>
          <strong>I = 8.7 A</strong>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-emerald-50 rounded-lg p-3 font-mono text-sm text-emerald-800">
          R = V ÷ I<br/>
          R = 230 ÷ 8.7<br/>
          <strong>R ≈ 26.4 Ω</strong>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-3">With a multimeter on resistance mode (heater disconnected), you'd expect ~26 Ω. A reading far from this indicates a damaged element.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Example 2 -->
  <div class="rounded-xl border border-gray-200 overflow-hidden">
    <div class="bg-gray-50 border-b border-gray-200 px-5 py-3 flex items-center gap-2">
      <span class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-[#1B3A5B] text-white text-xs font-bold flex items-center justify-center shrink-0">2</span>
      <p class="font-bold text-[#0D1B2A] text-sm">Diagnosing a voltage drop in a cable</p>
    </div>
    <div class="p-5">
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-3">Panel shows 230 V, motor terminals show 218 V — a 12 V drop at 20 A load. What is the cable resistance?</p>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-3 font-mono text-sm text-amber-800 mb-3">
        R = V_drop ÷ I<br/>
        R = 12 ÷ 20<br/>
        <strong>R = 0.6 Ω</strong>
      </div>
      <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">If the cable spec gives a lower value, the extra resistance points to a loose connection or corroded joint — exactly what a milli-ohmmeter or multimeter can pinpoint.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ── LIMITS ── -->
<h2 id="limits">The Limits of Ohm's Law</h2>

<Callout type="warning" title="When Ohm's Law doesn't apply">
  <p>Ohm's Law assumes the conductor's temperature is constant, the material is a linear (ohmic) conductor, and the measurement is at DC or quasi-static AC. At high frequencies, inductance and capacitance introduce <strong>reactance</strong> (X) — you need complex impedance <strong>Z = R + jX</strong>, measured by an LCR meter rather than a simple multimeter.</p>
</Callout>

<p>
  Understanding which regime your circuit falls into tells you which instrument to reach for. That's the practical value of knowing the physics, not just the formula.
</p>

